text: great question. It's something we spend a lot of time thinking about. And again, as I was saying before, probably the principal focus is in corporate credit. In summary, you've got to regard liquidity as uncertain. It's therefore something you shouldn't look to measure exactly. It's not a question of looking on a screen and saying, oh, well, the liquidity is this. You've got to model it. You've got to treat it as a probabilistic process. So I guess what I have in mind is there is a certain probability of a bond trading tomorrow, and it's that latent probability you're trying to forecast. And if you can forecast that well, then there's more chance that when your model generates a trade, you're actually able to execute it. So how do we approach that? You've got to think about a liquidity model for each particular area. So not just all corporate bonds as a whole, but do European bonds differ from US bonds, IG bonds differently liquid to high yield? How about emerging markets? So be specific. There are obvious drivers of liquidity at the bond level. So newer bonds, new bonds, new bonds, new bonds, new bonds, new bonds, new bonds, new bonds, trade more because they've just been issued and there's lots of activity. Older bonds tend to get locked up with institutional investors. Then there are patterns of liquidity across sectors with spread. And obviously, large firms have more liquid bonds than smaller firms. I think probably more fundamentally than that, having sort of modeled the characteristics at the bond level, you've got to decide if a bond doesn't trade too much over the recent period, is it because the bond is just illiquid? Or was it because the bond is just illiquid? And if it's just illiquid, then you've got to decide whether or not there was no particular interest in it, but it would have been available to trade if somebody had wanted to trade it. And that's where deliquates can come in. So there's another decision to make about how much to reflect a model based on past liquidity versus how much to take into account deliquates. And using a mixture of those things, I think we would believe is probably the ideal. Then there are questions like how much liquidity varies through time, both on a structural basis, as in generally, there's been improving liquidity and fixing them over time. And then there's also questions like how much liquidity varies through time, and the mechanisms associated with that. So the presence of ETFs, which tend to increase liquidity, but also what happens during shock periods. So I think you have to have an answer to all of those questions before you build a reasonably accurate liquidity model. But then you also have to recognize that it won't be fully accurate over time. The only way to really test these things properly is to use them out of sample. Then probably a couple more points. If we're thinking about backtests and building strategies, the question is, how aggressive to make the model. So we have this trade-off, which we typically think about. You could build a model only trading the most liquid instruments according to your model, in which case the chance of being able to trade that and get the trades on that the model wants to do would be maximized and everyone would have an easy life. But there's probably less alpha in that. Or you can build a more aggressive model, which goes down the liquidity spectrum, which means it's going to be harder to follow the model in practice. The transfer coefficient won't be 100%. By transfer coefficient, I mean, the correlation between actual positions and model positions, but there'll be more alpha in it. And that's a debate we have all the time. One more point on backtesting. You've got to be aware of whether you're being optimistic. So let's say we do a backtest with our liquidity model, and we assume that the model is giving us a good guide to what liquidity is there, but that could be wrong. So it's important to have a robustness concept from the point of view of backtests. A what if. What if liquidity turns out to be lower than we've assumed according to our model? What's the impact? What's the impact? What's the impact? What's the impact? What's the impact on backtesting? And you've got to be in a position, I think, to answer those questions. And then I think finally, something that we spend quite a lot of time on here at Blue Cave is the feedback loop. So we have a process called model management, and we look at lots of things in that. But one of them is questions around liquidity and transaction costs. So how good are our models in terms of forecasting liquidity? On how many occasions did we look for liquidity and it wasn't there? How well are our transaction cost models doing, et cetera? And then taking that and our analysis and feeding it back into the design is obviously key in terms of evolving those models to be as good as possible.
